player.seasonOutlook: Reynolds is a textbook Professional Hitter coming off four straight 20-homer seasons and back-to-back 20-10 campaigns. His batting average has not fallen below .260 in a full season and Reynolds has been an All-Star in two of the past four years since his fluke down year in 2020. While his defense in the outfield corners has fallen off a cliff, the Pirates have not seemed to mind nor have they indicated a positional change could be in the cards. Reynolds signed an eight-year contract extension in 2023 and will return to anchor the heart of the Pittsburgh order after batting exclusively out of the two hole last season -- typically where teams put their best hitter. Entering his age-30 season, Reynolds provides a stable floor in terms of skills and playing time.

Fried finds himself pitching for a new organization after spending the last nine seasons in the Atlanta organization, as the Yankees gave Fried a sizable deal despite the time missed in 2023 with a forearm strain as well as the neuritis in his pitching elbow in the middle of the 2024 season. The left-hander's ability to limit homers will be tested at Yankee Stadium, but left-center field being forgiving to his particular approach -- at least on paper -- should help balance things out in his favor. Fried throws seven different pitch types to both righties and lefties which puts hitters into uncomfortable situations. His ability to keep hitters off balance is why he is elite at limiting hard contact and why his ERA has just once been above 3.25 in a full season of work. The only risk associated with Fried would be a recurrence of the forearm issue from 2023 as the skills are more than steady.

A top prospect in his earlier seasons as a pro, Ramos' star sagged slightly before he burst onto the scene for the Giants with 20 homers across the final four months of 2024. His mastery of Triple-A ball across the prior year-plus earned him regular at-bats following Michael Conforto's injury in May, and Ramos flashed elite raw power metrics and well above-average speed. That did come with a wide platoon split (198 points of wOBA), a potential advantage to tuck away in ESPN's daily-transactions standard, but Ramos did show enough success against right-handers in the minors that he should take a step forward in 2025. Consider him to be a mid-to-late round pick in larger mixed leagues.

Busch, a first-round pick by the Dodgers in 2019, was traded to the Cubs last winter, opening up a path to playing time at the major-league level. Busch took advantage and showed what he's made of with an above-average offensive season at age 26 that included 21 homers and a .775 OPS across 567 plate appearances. Best of all for his 2025 outlook, Busch handled same-side pitching capably, slashing .258/.330/.382 against left-handed pitching. That performance along with his defense at first base, which the Cubs see as Gold Glove caliber, figure to keep Busch in the lineup nearly every day. First base has become rather top heavy in fantasy baseball and Busch makes for a decent fallback option for those that end up waiting at the position.

Duran is coming off a second consecutive 20-plus-save season, though his role in the Minnesota bullpen has been somewhat in fluid, more so than fantasy managers would like. As a rookie in 2022, he blew batters away with an 18.1 percent swinging-strike rate and an elite strikeout-minus-walk percentage. However, he has not been able to achieve the same level of overall success over the past two seasons. This past year saw a reduction in his strikeout rate while opponents hit 28 points higher against Duran. He also struggled to prevent runners from scoring when they got on base. It feels like a pitcher with this much swing and miss and such a high groundball rate should have better outcomes than what Duran has earned to date. The expected stats show what Duran's is capable of.

Considering the number of injuries that dogged him -- elbow trouble that cost him the first six weeks, forearm discomfort that cost him a June start, and a hamstring strain that sidelined him for 2 1/2 weeks in July -- Woo's 2024, which earned him a top-30 SP valuation in roto formats, was rather surprising. He has some of the best control in baseball, his 2.8% walk rate was best in baseball among those with at least 100 IP, and he had a 2.95 ERA over his last 29 big-league starts. Still, Woo's elbow and forearm issues raise future concerns about his durability. Monitor him carefully during spring training, but with better injury luck, he should deliver top-50 fantasy SP value.

Bogaerts started slowly last season, batting .219/.265/.316 over 47 games, perhaps due to learning a new position after an unexpected shift from shortstop to second base. He then suffered a nasty shoulder injury in May, costing him almost two months. After returning, Bogaerts settled in and hit .299/.338/.432 the rest of the way, in line with his 2023 production. His power never developed as hoped and now it's on the decline with three straight seasons of a falling barrel rate. However, Bogaerts has taken advantage of the rules aiding stolen bases, swiping 32 bases in 37 attempts over the past two years. His bat-to-ball skills are still solid, propping up his floor, but there isn't much upside in power or speed. Dual eligibility adds to Bogaerts' appeal, especially in daily leagues.

Springs debuted in late July following rehab from Tommy John surgery. He started seven games before being shut down for the season with left elbow fatigue in mid-September. His fastball was down a tick (velocity usually returns quickly), but the strikeout rate was in line with his pre-injury numbers. Springs walk rate was higher than normal, but diminished command immediately after returning is expected, especially since his signature pitch is a changeup which is slower to come around. The Athletics must have been encouraged by Springs' performance as they acquired the 32-year-old southpaw in December. Including rehab, the lefty totaled 65 innings, so expecting more than 120 frames in 2025 is aggressive. Springs is generally a matchup option, but that approach is clouded with the uncertainty of how Sutter Health Park in Sacramento will play.

Raleigh set new personal bests with 34 home runs and 100 RBI last season, finishing as the No. 2 catcher in traditional fantasy leagues despite a .220 batting average. The switch-hitting backstop has become a folk hero of sorts in Seattle with his majestic homers and timely hitting among other reasons. The fact that he's a significant plus behind the plate with his defense and framing helps Raleigh's chances of approaching or exceeding 600 plate appearances for the Mariners once again in 2025. The drain in batting average is significant but does not negate the value of his power and counting stats, which get a scarcity bump in two-catcher formats. Expect more of the same in 2025 with Raleigh overcoming the pitcher-friendly skew of his home ballpark.

Steele followed up his breakout season with very similar numbers around stints on the injured list with hamstring and elbow issues. His ERA and strikeout rate were nearly identical to his 2023 marks while his 1.10 WHIP was by far a career best. The left-hander returned from his elbow injury to make a couple starts for the Cubs at the end of the campaign, but they were abbreviated starts, and for many the dark cloud of uncertainty follows Steele into 2025. Among the 46 pitchers that have totaled 300 innings over the past two seasons, Steele ranks 16th in strikeout-minus-walk percentage, which demonstrates a high-end skills foundation. If he can stay healthy, Steele could ascend to legitimate ace status, but until he adds that missing piece, drafters should proceed with a degree of caution.

Miller's campaign was one of the most underappreciated -- not only in 2024, but across all historical rookie RP seasons. He became only the third rookie reliever to manage at least 25 saves, 100 strikeouts and a sub-2.50 ERA (Terry Forster, 1972; Craig Kimbrel, 2011), and among all pitchers with at least 50 IP in 2024, he led in strikeout rate (41.8%), average fastball velocity (100.9 mph) and Statcast-expected ERA (1.77). Miller, who previously had durability concerns, missed only two weeks' time to injury when he fractured his pinky punching a padded table, and a short-relief role seemed to suit his skill set. He has assumed a place as one of the game's best fantasy relievers, and it's a plus for 2025 that his Athletics made winter moves hinting at more of a push to compete.

A decently regarded prospect back in his Dodgers/Athletics days nearly a decade ago, Holmes finally reached the majors last June at the age of 28, parlaying his elite control and whiff-generating slider and curveball into a swingman role with the Braves. His performance impressed them enough that he earned the start in their must-win Game 162 against the Mets, in which he tossed four shutout innings of 1-hit, 7-K baseball, and winter chatter had him as a likely member of their 2025 Opening Day rotation. Whether Holmes, who before last season's 109 1/3 combined innings between the majors and minors hadn't exceeded 90 frames since 2017, has the stamina to hold up to a full-season starter's role is in question, but he's an intriguing flier in deep mixed and NL-only formats.

Casas' combination of power and patience makes him a perennial breakthrough candidate, but through three MLB seasons, he has had difficulty staying on the field. An ankle issue cost him two months of 2022, delaying his arrival in Boston, shoulder inflammation prematurely ended his 2023, and torn cartilage in his rib cage shelved him for more than three months of 2024. Casas was also the subject of winter trade rumors, though he'll begin 2025 again as Boston's first baseman, hoping for better luck in the health department. At his best, he could challenge for top-five positional status in any fantasy league.

The 2024 season was a disaster for Strider and his fantasy managers, as the No. 1 pitcher off most draft boards lasted just two starts before succumbing to season-ending elbow surgery -- though he had an internal brace procedure this time after having Tommy John surgery previously in 2019. That gives the right-hander hope of returning in the early stages of 2025. Stiil, there is always risk of setbacks or diminished performance in pitchers initially returning from such a significant operation. When healthy, Strider has been the game's best strikeout artist -- his 458 K's across his span of 54 healthy starts from May 2022-April 2024 were 51 more than the next-closest hurler -- so he'll naturally slide in as one of this year's top risk/reward pitcher picks. Monitor his rehabilitation throughout spring training, as his prognosis could drive his draft value as high as a top-25 SP pick or more of a late-round flier.

Pena now has three full major-league seasons under his belt. He has hit 20 homers in a season and he has also stolen 20 bases in a season, but the shortstop has been unable to accomplish both feats in the same campaign. Pena has the pull tendencies one would like to see from someone playing in Houston and hitting from the right side, but his high groundball rate limits his home-run power. Pena has improved his strikeout rate each season he has been in the majors, but he has not shown any willingness to accepts walks. Pena has also stolen double-digit bases each season, but his success rate has been below league average since the rule adjustments two seasons ago. His impatience puts him in the bottom half of the lineup which limits his overall upside, and it's a shame because Pena's numbers could be much better if he were setting the table ahead of the thunder in the lineup.

Garcia is coming off a career year in his ninth season in the organization since he signed as an amateur free agent in 2016. He earned the full-time spot at second base and hit all over the lineup over the course of the season. His lack of patience at the plate makes him better suited for the bottom half of the lineup, and as the Nationals continue to deepen their roster, it will become tougher for Garcia to get out of the lower half of the order unless some skills change. The good news is that he enjoyed his time down there last season, stealing 22 bases in 27 attempts despite just average speed since manager Dave Martinez has a lead foot on the running game. Garcia hit especially well at Nationals Park, slashing .329/.369/.549 with 14 homers at home compared to .233/.265/.335 with four homers on the road.

Steer experienced a down year in 2024, though his skills weren't far off from the previous more productive season. He was victimized by the baseball not carrying as well. Steer's flyball exit velocity was nearly the same as 2023, but the average distance dropped seven feet, costing him homers and BABIP. Furthermore, his batting average dropped 46 points, but his expected average fell only 17 points. Steer made up for the loss in power with 25 steals in 28 attempts (89% success rate). New Reds' manager Terry Francona gives the green light to players with a high success rate, so Steer should continue to be a quiet source of steals, with a good chance of a power rebound. He's only missed 10 games over the last two seasons, helping accumulate plentiful runs and RBI. Steer is slated to handle left field but could see action at the corner infield spots.

Jeffers had a strong 2023 season anchored by a career-best .276 average despite the 27.8 percent strikeout rate. He had rediscovered some of his 2022 power and repeated his home-run total from the season prior, but batted-ball fortunes really went his way that year, with a .359 BABIP driving the overall average. This past season, Jeffers reduced his strikeout rate by seven full percentage points, yet his batting average dropped 50 points year over year even as his batted-ball tendencies were nearly identical to 2023. We just don't often see batted-ball fortunes swing this wildly, but the .238 BABIP last year is what ultimately pulled his average down. Positive regression should help get Jeffers back over league average in that regard, but don't bank on 20-plus homers again.

Elbow inflammation put Valdez on the shelf early on last year, but he made a quick recovery and ended up totaling 176.1 innings during the 2024 regular season, pitching to a stellar 2.91 ERA and 1.11 WHIP. The left-hander has never been the most dominant arm in terms of strikeouts, but he generates groundballs at an incredibly high clip -- over 60 percent for his career -- mostly on the strength of his sinking fastball. High whiff rates on his secondaries suggest there may be some untapped strikeout potential, though Valdez is already 31 years old and paying for another level would be ill advised. Valdez leads the majors in wins with 44 over the past three seasons and will be in position to reach double digits for the Astros once again before potentially hitting free agency next winter.

Here's one of the most disappointing players of 2024, as his ADP in ESPN leagues was 18th overall, but he finished 55th on the Player Rater and tied for 170th in fantasy points. Rodriguez, only 24, has plenty of time to straighten things out.  Besides, his season wasn't a complete catastrophe, as he joined Mike Trout and Bobby Witt Jr. as the only three players in history to manage 20/20 numbers in each of their first three full MLB seasons. He also maintained strong underlying metrics in terms of his contact quality and raw speed, and he managed .295/.345/.486 rates, nine home runs and six stolen bases across his final 43 games after returning from a mid-year ankle injury. Rodriguez remains one of the game's most talented young players, albeit one who has shown a tendency for slow starts and is more of a rotisserie than points-based prospective star. He remains a strong early-round pick, especially in roto.

The Cardinals signed Gray to a three-year contract in November of 2023, but GM John Mozeliak made it clear this winter that lowering payroll is a priority heading into the 2025 season. With that, Gray is on the block, though he has a full no-trade clause. He won 13 games last season, his most since 2015, and finished third among qualified starters in strikeout percentage. Gray ended the season in the injured list with right forearm flexor tendonitis, but he was expected to have a normal offseason. Whether he stays in St. Louis or goes is a matter of little concern, since Gray is used to bouncing around the league. Health remains his biggest obstacle. The 35-year-old has averaged just over 150 innings per year over the past four seasons.

What a breakthrough Duran's 2024 campaign was! Few players have made as many all-around strides as he has over the past three years. He set personal bests in most every statistical category -- many of them by substantial margins -- culminating in his finishing 13th on our Player Rater and 18th overall in fantasy points scored. Most importantly, Duran, once a defensive liability, managed the eighth-best Statcast Fielding Run Value among outfielders, his strength in that department very much behind his MLB-leading 735 plate appearances. That amount of playing time will be tough to replicate, meaning some pull-back in his numbers is to be expected. Still, as a top-of-the-order Red Sox hitter, Duran should remain a top-50 fantasy performer regardless of format.

Bohm's name has been bandied about in trade rumors this winter ahead of his second year of arbitration eligibility. The Phillies are said to be eyeing a roster shakeup of sorts, but so far no team has met Philadelphia's asking price for the third baseman. Bohm had some tough times early in his big-league career, but he's been on the upswing since his infamous "I hate this place" incident in 2022, making his first All-Star team this past season. He hit five fewer homers than he did in 2023, totaling just 15 despite similar batted-ball numbers, following league-wide trends. Bohm has grounded into 41 double plays over the past two seasons which shows his below-average running ability, but at this point he's established as a dependable source of batting average and run production.

Following a December trade from Miami to Texas, Burger is projected to open the 2025 season as the Rangers' primary first baseman, replacing Nathaniel Lowe. Burger totaled 579 plate appearances last season around an early stint on the injured list with an intercostal strain, falling one home run short of reaching 30 for the second straight year. He has had to deal with a lot in his young career, including two tears of his left Achilles' tendon during his time in the minors, along with a pair of trades. While he's a rather one-dimensional player, Burger hits for enough average -- exactly .250 the last three seasons -- to complement the power and make him worthwhile in traditional fantasy formats. Those in OBP leagues will likely want to downgrade Burger given that he's allergic to walks (career 5.7 percent).

Swanson's 2024 was a lot like his 2023 in many ways. His rate stats were nearly identical, but 40 fewer plate appearances and a lower spot in the lineup affected his RBI total. Swanson was clearly battling some issues health-wise since he immediately had core muscle surgery once the season ended in order to be fully ready in time for spring training. By and large, Swanson continues to stay on the field and produce in all the counting categories, but 2022 may go down as his peak unless the prevailing winds in Wrigley happen to blow out more than they blow in. The numbers around his plate discipline are rather stable if slightly unspectacular. His strikeouts make it tough to envision him hitting over .270 again unless he is blessed with good batted-ball fortune.

Ragans' follow-up to his astonishing, late-2023 breakthrough went about as well as could possibly have been expected. He maintained almost every statistical gain across his by-far professional bests of 32 starts and 186 1/3 IP, with the only knock on his skills being his losing a tick on his average fastball velocity. Throwing 95.4 mph, however, makes him no slouch in terms of raw stuff, and pitching half of his games in one of the most pitcher-friendly environments helps bolster his case to be a true staff ace. Ragans should be drafted among the top 10 at his position, regardless of format.

After Brett Baty struggled and was returned to Triple-A, Vientos flourished as the Mets' regular third baseman across the season's final four months. He posted upper-tier raw power metrics while slashing more than 8% off his ground-ball rate, and his 24 homers from June 1 forward ranked fourth-best among third basemen and 12th-best in the majors. Still, Vientos' contact left a lot to be desired, as his 31.2% strikeout rate was seventh-worst over that same time span, which puts him at risk of lengthy cold spells and a low cumulative batting average. He's a legitimate power source with more rotisserie than points-based appeal, but be forewarned that he could be due for some regression in 2025.

?The Martian? figures to take over starting left field duties for the Yankees in 2025 and, while his defense often came into question during a late-season audition last year, his Triple-A dominance in 2023-24 (.325/.391/.495 rates, 7 HR, 18 SB in 53 games) reflects his immense offensive potential. Dominguez is one of the more important hitters to watch during spring training, as more patience and more lift in his swing than he showed in his two cups of coffee with the Yankees could do him a world of good. He should be a good source of stolen bases at the very least, a back-of-the-roster mixed-league player at the median, and a breakthrough player with building-block dynasty potential at his best.

The breakthrough didn't appear to happen for Pfaadt during his first full MLB season and, if you consider surface numbers only, his 6.60 ERA across his final 12 starts was unsightly. A check beneath the hood, however, reveals signs of growth that might ultimately lead to a front-of-a-fantasy-rotation role as early as 2025. Thanks to increased sinker usage, he added 10% to his ground-ball rate, and he boosted his strikeout rate during the season's second half, exemplified by his registering three double-digit strikeout performances over his final nine starts. Pfaadt, whom scouts regarded highly at the time of his MLB debut, is one of the better profit-potential starters you'll find in the middle rounds of mixed leagues.

Jones rode a stellar spring training into a spot in the Pirates' Opening Day rotation, then was one of baseball's most productive rookies for nearly three months. Through June 22, his nine quality starts paced his freshman class, and his 93 K's were second to only eventual AL Rookie of the Year Luis Gil. Unfortunately, a right lat strain cost Jones nearly eight weeks shortly thereafter, and he was inexplicably more reliant upon his curveball (his worst-performing pitch) for the rest of the way. Between Jones' quiet finish, and the presence of burgeoning superstar Paul Skenes within the same rotation, Jones might come at a relative discount entering 2025. His upside can't match that of Skenes, but Jones could be ready to take a step forward into the top-40 SP conversation.

Woodruff looked like a rising star for Milwaukee not long ago, earning All-Star selections in 2019 and 2021. However, he has missed the better part of two seasons due to injury, including all of 2024, after undergoing surgery in October of 2023 to repair the anterior capsule in his right shoulder. While the Brewers will not commit to Woodruff being ready for Opening Day 2025, he was said to be in a good spot and throwing multiple bullpen sessions per week in January. Entering his age-32 season, Woodruff is a wild card for both the Brewers and fantasy managers. The innings floor is zilch and the workload ceiling is capped, but Woodruff's excellent track record of performance (career 3.10 ERA, 1.05 WHIP) will likely tempt some to roll the dice outside the top 200 picks or so overall.

The Mets have given Soto's fantasy managers 765 million reasons to trust in his elite talent. He's one of six players in history to register a .400 OBP in each of his first seven seasons, and one of three from that group (Ted Williams, Frank Thomas) to also manage at least a 140 OPS-plus in each year. Soto's 201 career home runs before turning 26 are also tied for sixth-most in history, and he's the only player to register a top-15 fantasy point total among hitters in each of the past six seasons. He is the epitome of the high-floor, safe return on investment first-round pick, even if his profit potential is greater in leagues that reward his patience. Nevertheless, Soto could be headed for a prime-years uptick, playing the 2025 season at the age of 26.

Edman spent the first four months of the 2024 campaign on the injured list as he recovered from offseason wrist surgery and didn't see game action until after being traded from the Cardinals to the Dodgers at the deadline. The utility man played in 37 games during the regular season and had a .237/.294/.417 slash line with six homers and six steals, but he got on track during the playoffs with an .862 OPS in 67 plate appearances. Edman then inked a five-year extension with Los Angeles early in the offseason and he is expected to serve as the club's primary center fielder in 2025, though he'll likely still see some time at other positions. He's spent most of his career playing second base and shortstop, but he may be limited to outfield eligibility to begin the season since he made just one appearance at second base and 18 at shortstop last year. Edman averaged 12 home runs, 30 steals, 85 runs and 53 RBI across the three seasons prior to 2024, and that type of production is likely a best-case scenario in his age-30 campaign.

Wells began 2024 in a timeshare, then emerged as the Yankees' primary backstop. He does not light up his Statcast page, sporting average batted ball skills, but they often improve with young catchers. Wells' high flyball rate supports a solid power floor, but his platoon splits suggest sitting versus southpaws as all 13 of his homers came against right-handers. Strong defense and framing offer leeway to stay in the lineup and improve against southpaws, especially since there is little competition behind the plate in the Bronx after the trade of Jose Trevino to the Reds. Wells' solid plate skills generate a draftable floor, and there are several paths for more production, hence fantasy upside.

The Mets saw enough from Montas from a distance in 2024 to offer him two years and $34 million to join their rotation. Last season, Montas leaned on a mixture of his three fastballs (four-seamer, sinker, cutter) and dialed back the use of his splitter to mixed results. The four-seamer performed well as the league hit .206 against the pitch, but the cutter resulted in seven homers which is not ideal for a pitch that is designed to encourage weaker contact and not homers. Perhaps the layoff from the 2023 shoulder surgery affected his feel for the cutter. The Mets' offense should provide Montas with enough run support to win double-digit game for just the second time in his career, assuming Montas can make another 30 starts this season. Hopefully the rust is gone and his walks and homers level out.

Clase is the quintessential example of why fantasy managers shouldn't put too much stock into postseason performance. The regular season's most dominating closer -- his 469 fantasy points were 43 more than the next-closest reliever and his 0.61 ERA was third-best in history among pitchers with at least 50 IP -- he was touched up for two losses, one blown save and a 9.00 ERA across seven October appearances. Chalk that up to a pair of ill-placed sliders and an Aaron Judge wall-scraper, as Clase's 100-mph cutter and slider are otherwise typically next-to-impossible to hit. He's among the best at his craft, and, on a Guardians team sure to be scratching and clawing for W's yet again in 2025, he's as good an investment as closers come.

Yelich's troublesome back finally forced him under the knife in August, ending his season. Specifically, the procedure was a microdiscectomy, a spinal surgery to remove part or all of a bulging or herniated disc. While Yelich was still not cleared to swing a bat as of mid-December, the team is expecting him to be ready early on in spring training. The outfielder produced at a high level in between IL stints last season, slashing .315/.406/.504 with 11 homers and 21 steals in just 73 games. The back now being surgically repaired offers hope that Yelich could stay on the field and return to something close to his previous levels of production, though it would be unwise to expect him to return an MVP level for the Brewers at 33 years old.

The centerpiece of the 2023-24 offseason's Juan Soto trade, King proved every bit as capable a starting pitcher across 30 starts for the Padres last season as he was over an eight-start stint for the Yankees to conclude 2023. In fact, King was one of only four pitchers to strike out at least 200 batters with a sub-3.00 ERA, joining both Cy Young Award winners (Chris Sale, Tarik Skubal) and Zack Wheeler. He only strengthened his underlying numbers over the season's second half, getting a whiff nearly one-third of the time hitters swung at any of his pitches. It sets up the right-hander well for a similarly productive 2025, albeit with some risk of ERA regression, as his Statcast xERA should be nearly three-quarters of a run higher. Still, that's a top-20 capable fantasy starter regardless of format.

After inking the right-hander to a six-year contract extension in early March, Boston rolled out the red carpet for Bello on Opening Day, and Bello even pitched like a frontline starter for a brief stretch. Ultimately, his numbers resembled those of a back-end starter. His season was interrupted by a lat injury in late April which necessitated a trip to the injured list, and Bello found himself struggling with walks upon his return, issuing three or more free passes 10 times following his activation in May. His overall walk rate was 9.1 percent, and that is walking a fine line when the pitcher has a strikeout rate barely above 20 percent for their career. Bello generally does a good job of keeping the ball in the park with his sinker-slider-changeup mix, though lefties can touch him up. Fantasy managers should approach Bello with caution as he attempts to navigate the tough AL East once again in 2025.

Crochet didn't merely break out in his first season back in a pitching rotation since his Tennessee days -- his 2024 performance was historic. He became the first pitcher in the modern era to strike out at least 140 batters with 20 walks or fewer through his first 18 career starts, and seven consecutive strikeouts to begin his Sept. 1 start tied an AL record. Despite the White Sox's concerns about his workload, which increased over the course of the summer, Crochet maintained elite underlying skills, even if his 5.12 second-half ERA belied his talent. The Red Sox acquired him with the hopes he can further blossom into their staff ace. Considering his arrow pointed nowhere but up for the entirety of 2024, there's reason to believe he will. Crochet is a building-block pitcher for fantasy purposes.

After teasing a late-career power surge in 2023, Diaz reverted to his previous power levels last season. Overall, Diaz continues to sport elite quality of contact metrics, but since he hits grounders more than half of the time, he is unable to take full advantage. Not only did Diaz's power drop, but his batting average with runners in scoring position fell 90 points, limiting his RBI. After carrying a double-digit walk rate over the previous five seasons, Diaz's patience waned last season, leaving him with the second-lowest OBP of his career. Diaz is best suited for points leagues, where his high doubles total can help mitigate fewer homers. Look for a rebound, but 2023 will likely go down as Diaz's career year.

Consistency is tough to find in the late innings. Even the greats like Hader endure some statistical variance -- he had a 5.22 ERA in a difficult 2022 season -- and it comes with the territory of facing the best hitters in the world in the highest-leverage spots night after night. Hader tallied 34 saves in his first year with Houston and has now racked up 30-plus saves in each of the last five full MLB seasons. The left-hander occasionally toes the line with walks and home runs, but his sinking fastball and swing-and-miss slider form a highly effective 1-2 punch. While the Astros have done some retooling this winter, but there is little reason to think Hader won't be the closer for Houston in 2025, with the flexibility and dominance to exceed 100 strikeouts in relief.

Ozuna has been on an amazing two-year run since nearly playing his way out of Atlanta with consecutive terrible seasons in 2021 and 2022. He served exclusively as a designated hitter and in fact started all 162 games at DH last season, returning to elite-level run production once again after it once looked as if 2017 was going to be his peak. Ozuna has driven in 100 runs in each of the past two seasons, and it was all the more impressive in 2024 considering the amount of injuries to the Atlanta lineup over the course of the season. The counting stats seem ultra stable, though his batting average has ranged from .213 to .338 over the past five seasons despite relatively stable walk and strikeout rates, which is a reminder of how is still left up to the randomness of the machinations of baseball. Ozuna may never score 100 runs, but there is little reason to suspect he cannot continue to this current run of success.

While many might regard Torres' career thus far as a disappointment, he has nevertheless carved out a plenty productive role for himself. Over his seven MLB seasons, his 138 home runs rank third-most among second basemen and he's one of only four at the position with at least 100 homers and 50 steals. Torres did benefit from the hitter-friendly home environment of Yankee Stadium, as well as the often potent Yankees lineup, so some regression is to be expected now that he's a member of the Tigers. Still, Torres seems to have settled in as an annual 25-HR, 10-SB, .265-hitting type with top-10 positional fantasy value. Plus, he did finish an underwhelming 2024 on a high note (.297/.369/.453, 7 HR over his final 45 games, playoffs included). Expect similar value from him in 2025.

Whereas most catchers wear down rather quickly due the rigors of the position, Perez is still running strong at nearly 35 years old. He exceeded 100 RBI last season for the second time in his career and surged past 20 homers once again en route to his fifth Silver Slugger Award. Perez is the active leader in games played at catcher and 58th on the all-time list. The Royals have made a concerted effort to limit Perez's time behind the plate in recent years, giving him more time at first base and DH, which makes all the sense in the world given the mileage on Perez's knees and with Freddy Fermin proving plenty capable of helping with the workload. Perez is firmly in the old-and-boring category, but his track record of power production from the catcher spot should keep his services in high demand in fantasy baseball.

The aging curve appears to have taken hold with Goldschmidt, as his age-37 season saw him post his worst strikeout, walk and home run rates and the lowest isolated power and batting averages of his 14-year MLB career. He did, however, hit 20 home runs across his final 117 games, while mashing lefties (.295/.366/.473), and the move from Busch Stadium to Yankee Stadium should only help him in terms of park factors. Goldschmidt might have one more top-10 fantasy 1B season left in his bat, though his recent trend makes him a wiser player to target for your mixed-league corner infield position.

Oblique, shoulder and rib injuries cost him the final month of 2023 and the entirety of 2024, but McLain returned to action during the Arizona Fall League and delivered .240/.356/.520 rates while seeing time at three different positions (2B, 3B and CF). He'll be ready to compete for a utility role this spring and, with a strong March, should be ready to pick up where he last left off -- as a potential 25/25 player. McLain does have a lot of swing-and-miss in his game, putting him at risk for slumps and a low batting average, but he's an attractive mid-round pick, with slightly more appeal in rotisserie than points-based leagues.

After a sluggish start to his Mets career, Lindor has recaptured his form as one of baseball's best all-around players. He has managed at least 31 home runs, 91 RBI, 29 stolen bases and 107 runs scored in both of the last two seasons, and showed decidedly improved raw power metrics. In fact, Lindor's strong finish to 2024 -- he hit .306/.368/.575 with 16 homers after the All-Star break -- hints at a possibly larger step forward in 2025. As the Mets made a big splash in free agency -- some guy named Soto -- Lindor's surging metrics come at an opportune time, as the team's offense should enjoy a noticeable boost from top to bottom. Lindor is a top-25 overall pick who, with some good fortune, could deliver first-round fantasy production.

Suarez made the most of his change of scenery and had his best season at the plate since 2019. That 2019 season will not be replicated, but for Suarez to hit 30 homers and drive in 100-plus in a neutral offensive environment with baseballs that were not traveling as far last year says something. Suarez continues to be a fastball destroyer and he remains quite capable of punishing mistakes. The third baseman still has a good amount of swing and miss in his game, which can lead to some serious peaks and valleys. To that point, he had just 10 homers and a .216/.302/.366 line at the All Star break last season. Suarez hitting 20 homers with a .307/.341/.602 line in the second half won some leagues and quieted the doubters who thought 2023 was the start of an acceleration into the aging curve.

Castro has carved out a highly valuable role as a super utilityman with the Twins, perfect for a natural shortstop with plus athleticism. The stolen bases rendering so him so useful in 2023 declined to 14 thefts last year, but additional playing time between five positions allowed Castro to maintain status as a fantasy asset. There are signs of progress with noticeable increases in exit velocity and Hard Hit, fueling a career-high of 47 extra-base hits. Four position eligibility adds to his allure, though he isn't assured of a starting job. Second base is his best opportunity, but even if he remains in a reserve capacity, Castro can be helpful, especially in daily leagues.

Frelick's versatility may be his best asset. He played all three outfield positions last season and made enough of an impression in his limited time at third base that manager Pat Murphy has already stated Frelick will get a chance to compete for that spot this spring. It would be a highly unusual profile at third base because Frelick has a fraction of the pop of even an average third baseman these days. Frelick's fantasy value is anchored to his speed and ability to score runs. He is also not going to see much action against lefty starters, so repeating 500-plus plate appearances is a challenge on paper. Murphy's lead foot with the running game is the ultimate draw with Frelick since we know he is going to run when he reaches base. Fantasy managers simply must have the right roster build to add this empty speed in the endgame.

Morel was batting just .199/.302/.373 when the Cubs dealt him to the Rays just before the trade deadline. He performed even worse in the junior circuit, posting a .191/.258/.289 line with Tampa Bay. Morel still managed his second 20-homer season while demonstrating progress with more walks and fewer strikeouts. Morel's poor defense will be hidden in left field, where he's ticketed to play regularly. There's potential for 30 homers if he reverts to his pull-heavy approach from 2023, and eligibility at second base and third base -- with bonus outfield eligibility in leagues with a 10-game minimum -- helps soften the blow of the low average.

Oh, what his 2024 season might have been had he come to contract terms before March 19. Snell struggled to get up to speed across the season's first three months, spending time on the IL due to adductor and groin issues, but once he found his groove, he managed a 1.23 ERA, a 38.1% strikeout rate and the majors' most fantasy points across his final 14 starts. Snell does have a history of statistical peaks over seasonal portions rather than the whole, but he also possesses multiple Cy Young Awards (2018, 2023), and his second-best-in-baseball 2.82 ERA (minimum 300 innings) across the past three seasons points to him likely being at an overall high point. The Dodgers should do well managing his workload and getting the most out of him, and there's a very real chance that Snell will rebound to rank among his position's best performers.

Nola is only a one-time All-Star, with his lone All-Star appearance coming back in 2018. While he may not receive much attention nationally, Nola is one of the game's most dependable arms, having made at least 32 starts in each of the last six full MLB seasons. He shaved almost a run off his ERA in 2024 and fell just three strikeouts short of reaching 200 Ks for the sixth consecutive full season. His knuckle curve remains an excellent swing-and-miss pitch and his four-seamer was more effective last year, as opponents combined to bat just .168 against the offering. The right-hander can get bit by the long ball on occasion, and in fact Nola led the National League in homers allowed last season. That said, he still does so much well and won't turn 32 until June. Until further notice, Nola should be considered one of the best No. 2 starters in baseball.

Gausman wasn't quite himself last year after a bout of shoulder fatigue in spring training interrupted his preparations for the start of the season. The right-hander's velocity was down a tick in 2024 -- several ticks early on -- and the strikeouts dipped along with it. His surface numbers improved over the final two months, but the strikeouts never really rebounded, as he was below a 20 percent K rate in both August and September. Just one year ago, Gausman was treated as a borderline ace following a late-career breakout built on the strength of his trademark splitter. The market has perhaps overcorrected heading into 2025, though the massive decline in whiffs and tough division leave performance question marks and provide reason to invest elsewhere. Now 34, Gausman has two years remaining on his deal with the Blue Jays.

Bassitt's ERA last year was half a run higher than the previous season, while his 1.46 WHIP in 2024 was the second highest among qualified starters. Bassitt's walk rate was his highest since 2018, but the bigger culprit was a .333 BABIP, third highest among all qualifiers. A bloated hit rate can be misfortune, but it can also be a sign of a pitcher being more hittable. Bassitt's strikeout rate is a tick below league average, so he needs to minimize traffic to be effective. Bassitt's track record warrants the benefit of the doubt, but he'll be 36 years old this season, so a full rebound will be challenging. Pitching in the AL East isn't conducive to favorable matchups, relegating Bassitt to deep leagues, at least until he demonstrates a return to his previous control levels.

After several years spent toiling in mediocrity between the rotation and bullpen, Lugo enjoyed a surprise breakout at 34 years old in his first season as a member of the Royals' rotation. He was a first-time All-Star and won 16 games, tied for second in the American League. Lugo surged past 200 innings for the first time ever after previously topping out at 146.1 frames in 2023. It's rather tough to buy into given Lugo's lack of strikeouts or track record, but he has one of the best defenses in the majors behind him. The righty had nine different pitches categorized by Statcast last season, and that ability to throw the kitchen sink helps keep opposing hitters off balance and off his four-seam fastball. He may be a fade for some, but it's possible Lugo found something with Kansas City that will allow him to continue beating the estimators in 2025.

Control has always been an issue for Diaz, but he fanned over 30 percent of the batters he faced in his first two seasons, so he was able to get away with a high walk rate. Last season, Diaz's walk rate remained high, but his strikeout rate plummeted to 22.7 percent. He still saved 28 games in 32 chances, but his ratios were high, and his 55 strikeouts were the third fewest among relievers that logged at least 25 saves. Diaz only throws a four-seam fastball and slider, and last season his fastball velocity dipped for the second straight season. His swinging-strike rate also fell for the second consecutive year. The trends are a bit troubling, but Diaz could still regain some fastball zip. There isn't anyone to immediately challenge Diaz for saves and new manager Terry Francona historically prefers a set closer, but Diaz's job security can't be considered high until he regains dominance.

After four seasons serving as one of baseball's most unhittable relievers -- both his 1.75 ERA and .146 BAA from 2020-23 were easily best in the game -- Williams' 2024 swung his skill set into risk/reward territory. Back issues that plagued him late in 2023 resurfaced during spring training, costing him four months, but upon his return he hardly skipped a beat. Among pitchers with at least 20 IP following his July 28 activation, Williams' 43.2% strikeout rate ranked second, his 14 saves tied for fourth and his .133 BAA ranked 10th. The Yankees acquired him during the winter to take over as their closer, their confidence signaling more ?reward? to his fantasy calculus. If his back issues are indeed behind him, he'll make another run at the position's top spot.

Suarez began the 2024 season by going 9-0 with a minuscule 1.36 ERA and 0.79 WHIP across his first 66 innings, only to slide to 3-8 with a 5.10 ERA and 1.52 WHIP over his subsequent 17 starts. The left-hander was said to be dealing with back tightness around the All-Star break and he eventually landed on the injured list as a result of the injury. Despite the way his season trended, it still has to be considered a highly successful campaign, one that further established Suarez as a quality mid-rotation starter in MLB. He is not the most dominant arm in terms of strikeouts, but Suarez keeps the ball on the ground and has one of the National League's best offenses to power him to wins. It's also not crazy to hold out hope that Suarez may still be able to add to his workload in his age-29 season after making the transition from the bullpen a few years ago.

Martinez began the season with Triple-A Reno, but after punching out 14 hitters in 6.2 innings, he was called up in mid-April. Early on, he worked in low-leverage scenarios, notching his first hold June 4. Martinez then serves as a setup man until August when he took over as the primary closer for Arizona. He converted eight of nine chances over the final two months and Martinez has stuff to continue closing as he averages triple digits on his four-seam fastball and sinker, though can struggle to locate on occasion. His WHIP will be high with the walks, so saves will come with ratio baggage. Just 23 years old, Martinez can certainly learn to throw more strikes. He'll enter the season as the favorite for saves in the desert, though A.J. Puk looms if Martinez's control issues yield too many blown saves.

Lee suffered a season-ending shoulder injury in May when he crashed into the outfield fence at Oracle Park, necessitating surgery. The expectation is that Lee will be a full go for the start of spring training in 2025 as he enters Year 2 of a six-year contract with the Giants following a storied career with the Kiwoom Heroes of the Korea Baseball Organization. At age 25, Lee debuted in the majors with a .289 batting average across his first 20 games before dipping to .226 across his subsequent 17 games. It was a rather tiny sample in the end, but the contact that he was known for in the KBO translated, with Lee striking out just 13 times across 158 plate appearances. The big question is whether Lee can tap into enough power to be worthwhile in mixed leagues, but that may be tough in San Francisco. It's also possible that Lee could lose out on some at-bats against left-handed pitching.

It appeared that Detmers' long-awaited breakthrough was happening early in 2024, as he recorded a 3.12 ERA and 1.15 WHIP after five starts. Unfortunately, the script suddenly flipped, and he logged a 9.85 ERA and 1.87 WHIP over his next six outings. Detmers was then demoted to Triple-A Salt Lake, but he to make five starts in September and struggled with an 8.14 ERA and 1.77 WHIP. His 3.86 xFIP and 27.9% strikeout rate offer some room for optimism, but Detmers needs more consistent command and control. Still just 25 years old, there are worse speculative plays, but Detmers will have to earn an Opening Day rotation spot after the Angels fortified their staff with Yusei Kikuchi and Kyle Hendricks.

Fresh off his unanimous 2023 NL Rookie of the Year campaign -- one that saw him become the first rookie in baseball history with at least 25 home runs and 50 stolen bases -- Carroll spent the first half of 2024 making a compelling case for fantasy bust of the year. A near-universal first round pick, he entered the All-Star break batting just .213 with five home runs, three of which came in the eight days leading into it, as he struggled throughout to adapt to swing changes he had implemented the prior winter. Carroll finally got it together during the second half, hitting .259/.351/.568 with 17 homers and 17 steals in 64 games, a welcome sign that the rotisserie superstar of old had returned. Just 24, Carroll would surely benefit from better luck on balls in play, but all signs have him returning to near top-10 form in 2025. It's just a year too late for those who drafted him that way last spring.
